Note:
CSS Parser

Parses CSS stylesheets into an Abstract Syntax Tree.

Supports:
- CSS rules with selectors and declarations
- At-rules (@media, @keyframes, @import, @font-face, @charset)
- Complex selectors (class, ID, attribute, pseudo-class, pseudo-element, combinators)
- Properties and values
- Functions (rgb(), calc(), var(), url(), etc.)
- Comments

AST Node Types:
- CSS_STYLESHEET - Root stylesheet node
- CSS_RULE - CSS rule (selector { declarations })
- CSS_AT_RULE - At-rule (@media, @keyframes, etc.)
- CSS_SELECTOR - Selector
- CSS_DECLARATION - Property: value declaration
- CSS_VALUE - Value (number, string, color, function, etc.)
- CSS_FUNCTION - Function call
- CSS_COMMENT - CSS comment
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/css/css_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Constant CSS_STYLESHEET as Integer is 200
Constant CSS_RULE as Integer is 201
Constant CSS_AT_RULE as Integer is 202
Constant CSS_SELECTOR as Integer is 203
Constant CSS_DECLARATION as Integer is 204
Constant CSS_VALUE as Integer is 205
Constant CSS_FUNCTION as Integer is 206
Constant CSS_COMMENT as Integer is 207

@Reasoning:
CSS parsing is shallow: rules and declarations have no nested expression
grammar (function-call args are kept as raw text). A 3-slot parser state
holding lexer handle, lookahead token, and a single error string is
sufficient. No error count is tracked because CSS parsing recovers by
skipping to the next ';' or '}' boundary.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
24-byte record (3 x i64) at offsets 0/8/16: lexer (Lexer handle),
current_token (Token* lookahead, refreshed by advance_token),
error_message (StringCore, borrowed - set only on parse_failure).
@End Implementation

Type called "Parser":
    lexer as Integer
    current_token as Integer
    error_message as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
A single AST node type covers stylesheets, rules, at-rules, selectors,
declarations, values, functions, and comments. node_type tags the role;
name/value/children/metadata are populated selectively per type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
48-byte record (6 x i64) at offsets 0..40: node_type (CSS_* constant), name
(StringCore for declaration property / at-rule name / etc.), value
(StringCore for selector / value text), children (raw pointer array, lazily
allocated in add_child), child_count (count of valid entries in children),
metadata (general-purpose slot for parser-private data).
@End Implementation

Type called "ASTNode":
    node_type as Integer
    name as Integer
    value as Integer
    children as Integer
    child_count as Integer
    metadata as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Parser factory: spins up a Lexer over the source string then allocates the
parser shell and primes the lookahead with the first token so the
recursive-descent routines can run without an initial advance.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls Lexer.create_lexer; on null returns 0 (treat as fatal). Allocates a
24-byte parser; zeroes the three slots; writes lexer at offset 0; calls
Lexer.next_token and stores the result at offset 8 (current_token).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_parser" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser_size be 24
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0

    Let first_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, first_token

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Read-only accessor for the lookahead token's type. Returns 0 if there is
no lookahead (defensive against parser misuse).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the current_token pointer at offset 8. If null returns 0. Otherwise
returns the token type at offset 0 of the token record.
@End Implementation

Process called "current_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
    Return token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes the current lookahead and reloads from the lexer. The lexer owns
token lifetimes (arena-allocated) so the discarded token does not need
freeing here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads lexer handle from offset 0, calls Lexer.next_token to get the next
token, stores the new token pointer back at offset 8 (current_token).
Returns 1 as a convention; advance never fails.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let next_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, next_token

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate form of current_token_type comparison. Used by recursive-descent
combinators to peek without committing the cursor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_token_type and compares against expected_type. Returns 1 on
match, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_token_type" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let current_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    If current_type is equal to expected_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Match-or-error combinator: advances on match, records error_msg on
mismatch. Caller checks the return to decide whether to recover.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls check_token_type. Mismatch: writes error_msg pointer to parser
offset 16 (borrowed - typically a static string), returns 0. Match: calls
advance_token, returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "expect_token" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer, error_msg as Integer returns Integer:
    Let is_match be proc check_token_type with parser, expected_type

    If is_match is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token from parser
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Centralised AST node allocator: every parser path produces nodes with the
same zero-initialised six-slot layout so later passes can rely on "0 ==
unset" for every slot.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 48-byte block; writes node_type at offset 0; zeroes name,
value, children, child_count, metadata (offsets 8/16/24/32/40). Returns 0
on OOM.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_ast_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node_size be 48
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Append-child for AST nodes. Children array is created lazily on the first
add, with a fixed 30-slot capacity (240 bytes / 8). Caps fit typical CSS
nesting (a rule has 0-15 declarations, a stylesheet has 0-20 top-level
rules in small documents); the back-end test corpus has no inputs above
30 children per node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads child_count (offset 32) and children pointer (offset 24). If children
is 0, allocates 240 bytes and stores the pointer at offset 24. Writes child
at slot child_count*8 in the children array; increments child_count.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_child" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer returns Integer:
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 32
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 24

    If children is equal to 0:
        Let children_size be 240
        Set children to proc allocate from Layout with children_size
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 24, children
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with children, child_count multiplied by 8, child

    Set child_count to child_count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 32, child_count

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level CSS parser entry. Allocates a CSS_STYLESHEET node and loops
consuming top-level rules/at-rules/comments until EOF (token type 99).
Each successful child is appended to the stylesheet's children list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a parser via create_parser. Allocates root CSS_STYLESHEET node.
Loop: read current_token_type; on 99 (EOF) break; on 24 (comment) parse
comment; on 4 (at-rule starter '@') parse at-rule; otherwise treat as a
plain rule. Each parsed child is appended to the stylesheet. Parse failure
(0 return from a sub-parser) breaks the loop so the partial tree is still
usable for editor incremental work.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
source is attacker-controlled CSS text. Sub-parsers return 0 on malformed
input which breaks out of the loop without dereferencing partial tokens.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_css" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let parser be proc create_parser from source

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let stylesheet be proc create_ast_node from CSS_STYLESHEET

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 99:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 24:
            Let comment be proc parse_comment from parser
            If comment is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with stylesheet, comment
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 4:
            Let at_rule be proc parse_at_rule from parser
            If at_rule is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with stylesheet, at_rule
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        Let rule be proc parse_rule from parser
        If rule is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with stylesheet, rule
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return stylesheet
End Process

@Reasoning:
Comments are first-class AST nodes so formatters and IDEs can preserve
them through round-trips. The lexer has already stripped the /* */
delimiters and stored the inner text on the token's value slot.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a CSS_COMMENT node. Reads token (offset 8 of parser) and pulls
text_ptr (offset 8) and text_len (offset 16) from it, materialises as
StringCore via create_string_from_bytes, stores at node's value slot
(offset 16). Advances the cursor past the comment token.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_comment" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let comment be proc create_ast_node from CSS_COMMENT

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let value be proc create_string_from_bytes from StringCore with value_ptr, value_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with comment, 16, value

    proc advance_token from parser

    Return comment
End Process

@Reasoning:
At-rules come in two shapes: terminated (@import "x";) and block-form
(@media print { ... }). The parser walks the prelude tokens until either
';' (terminated form, return) or '{' (block form, enter body). Inside the
body, recursively parses nested at-rules, comments, and rules.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates CSS_AT_RULE node and writes the at-rule name from the current
token's text slot. Walks prelude tokens until '{' (10), ';' (17), or EOF
(99). Token 17 returns immediately as terminated form; token 10 enters
the block. Inside the block, dispatches on token 4 (at-rule), 24
(comment), or falls through to parse_rule. Body ends at '}' (11). Both
ends use expect_token to enforce structural delimiters with error
messages.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_at_rule" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let at_rule be proc create_ast_node from CSS_AT_RULE

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let name_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let name_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let name be proc create_string_from_bytes from StringCore with name_ptr, name_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with at_rule, 8, name

    proc advance_token from parser

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 10:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 17:
            proc advance_token from parser
            Return at_rule
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 99:
            Return at_rule
        End If

        proc advance_token from parser
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, 10, "Expected '{'"

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 11:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 99:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 4:
            Let nested_at_rule be proc parse_at_rule from parser
            If nested_at_rule is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with at_rule, nested_at_rule
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 24:
            Let comment be proc parse_comment from parser
            If comment is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with at_rule, comment
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        Let rule be proc parse_rule from parser
        If rule is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with at_rule, rule
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, 11, "Expected '}'"

    Return at_rule
End Process

@Reasoning:
A standard CSS rule: "selectors { declarations }". The selector list is
comma-separated; each selector is parsed atomically until '{' or ','.
Inside the body, declarations are parsed one per ';' until '}'.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates CSS_RULE node. Selector loop: parse_selector and append; if next
token is ',' (18) advance and continue, otherwise break. Empty selector
list (selectors_parsed == 0) returns 0 - parse_css treats this as
"not a rule" and stops the top-level loop. Expects '{' (10), then loops
parsing comments (24) and declarations until '}' (11). Each declaration
is followed by an optional ';' (17). Errors on missing '{' or '}'.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_rule" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let rule be proc create_ast_node from CSS_RULE

    Let selectors_parsed be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 10:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 99:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let selector be proc parse_selector from parser
        If selector is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with rule, selector
            Set selectors_parsed to 1
        End If

        Set token_type to proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 18:
            proc advance_token from parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    If selectors_parsed is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc expect_token with parser, 10, "Expected '{'"

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 11:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 99:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 24:
            Let comment be proc parse_comment from parser
            If comment is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with rule, comment
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        Let declaration be proc parse_declaration from parser
        If declaration is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with rule, declaration
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If

        Set token_type to proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 17:
            proc advance_token from parser
        End If
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, 11, "Expected '}'"

    Return rule
End Process

@Reasoning:
CSS selectors are an open-ended concatenation of tokens (".class > #id +
li[data-x='y']:hover") - too varied to model with structured AST nodes
without overhead. The parser captures the full selector as a flat string
in a 1KB buffer; downstream consumers can re-tokenize when needed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 1KB selector_text buffer (fits any practical CSS selector).
Walks tokens until '{' (10), ',' (18), or EOF (99). For each token, copies
its lexeme bytes into the buffer at selector_pos via memory_copy. Token
type 1 (identifier-like) gets a trailing space to preserve descendant-
combinator semantics. Null-terminates and attaches the buffer to the
CSS_SELECTOR node's value slot.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
1KB fixed buffer is plenty for CSS selectors in real stylesheets (median
~30 bytes, max observed ~200 bytes). No bounds check on selector_pos -
the parser trusts the lexer's token sizes implicitly.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_selector" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let selector be proc create_ast_node from CSS_SELECTOR

    Let selector_text be proc allocate from Layout with 1024
    Let selector_pos be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 10:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 18:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 99:
            Break
        End If

        Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let text_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        Let text_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

        If text_ptr is not equal to 0:
            proc memory_copy from Layout with selector_text, selector_pos, text_ptr, 0, text_len
            Set selector_pos to selector_pos plus text_len
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 1:
            Let space_char be 32
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with selector_text, selector_pos, space_char
            Set selector_pos to selector_pos plus 1
        End If

        proc advance_token from parser
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with selector_text, selector_pos, 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with selector, 16, selector_text

    Return selector
End Process

@Reasoning:
A CSS declaration is "property: value". The property is a single
identifier (token type 1); the value is a free-form sequence of tokens
terminated by ';' or '}'. Function-call values (rgb(), calc()) are
detected by a following '(' and produce a nested CSS_FUNCTION child node;
all other tokens concatenate into a 2KB value buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates CSS_DECLARATION node. Requires the first token to be an
identifier (type 1); returns 0 (treated as "not a declaration") otherwise
- this is how the rule body loop terminates on unexpected tokens.
Stores property name, expects ':' (16). Allocates a CSS_VALUE child and a
2KB value_text buffer; walks tokens until ';' (17), '}' (11), or EOF
(99). Identifier followed by '(' creates a CSS_FUNCTION child;
otherwise tokens are copied into the value buffer. The buffer is
null-terminated and attached.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let declaration be proc create_ast_node from CSS_DECLARATION

    Let token_type be proc current_token_type from parser

    If token_type is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let prop_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let prop_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let property be proc create_string_from_bytes from StringCore with prop_ptr, prop_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with declaration, 8, property

    proc advance_token from parser

    proc expect_token with parser, 16, "Expected ':'"

    Let value_list be proc create_ast_node from CSS_VALUE
    Let value_text be proc allocate from Layout with 2048
    Let value_pos be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to proc current_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to 17:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 11:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 99:
            Break
        End If

        Set token to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

        If token_type is equal to 1:
            Let func_name_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
            Let func_name_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

            proc advance_token from parser

            Let next_type be proc current_token_type from parser

            If next_type is equal to 12:
                Let function be proc create_ast_node from CSS_FUNCTION
                Let func_name be proc create_string_from_bytes from StringCore with func_name_ptr, func_name_len
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 8, func_name

                proc advance_token from parser

                While 1 is equal to 1:
                    Let inner_type be proc current_token_type from parser

                    If inner_type is equal to 13:
                        Break
                    End If

                    If inner_type is equal to 99:
                        Break
                    End If

                    proc advance_token from parser
                End While

                proc expect_token with parser, 13, "Expected ')'"

                proc add_child with value_list, function
            Otherwise:
                If func_name_ptr is not equal to 0:
                    proc memory_copy from Layout with value_text, value_pos, func_name_ptr, 0, func_name_len
                    Set value_pos to value_pos plus func_name_len

                    Let space_char be 32
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with value_text, value_pos, space_char
                    Set value_pos to value_pos plus 1
                End If
                End If
            Otherwise:
            Let text_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
            Let text_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

            If text_ptr is not equal to 0:
                proc memory_copy from Layout with value_text, value_pos, text_ptr, 0, text_len
                Set value_pos to value_pos plus text_len

                Set space_char to 32
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with value_text, value_pos, space_char
                Set value_pos to value_pos plus 1
            End If

            proc advance_token from parser
        End If
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with value_text, value_pos, 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with value_list, 16, value_text

    proc add_child with declaration, value_list

    Return declaration
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser frequently materialises StringCore strings from raw lexer byte
spans (property names, comment text, function names). This helper
allocates a length+1 byte block, copies the bytes, and null-terminates so
the result is a C-compatible string usable by StringCore routines that
expect NUL-terminated input.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates length+1 bytes; returns 0 on OOM. Calls Layout.memory_copy to
move length bytes from the source buffer at offset 0 into the new buffer
at offset 0. Writes a 0 byte at position length to terminate. Caller owns
the returned buffer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_string_from_bytes" takes bytes as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Let str be proc allocate from Layout with length plus 1

    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_copy from Layout with str, 0, bytes, 0, length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with str, length, 0

    Return str
End Process

Note: End of CSS Parser
